===Etymology===
{{PIE root|en|bʰeh₂|id=shine}}
From {{bor|en|fro|epyphanie}}, from {{der|en|LL.|epiphania}}, from {{der|en|grc|ἐπιφάνεια||manifestation, striking appearance}}, from {{m|grc|ἐπιφαίνω||I appear, display}}, from {{m|grc|ἐπί||upon}} + {{m|grc|φαίνω||I shine, appear}}. English [[Epiphany]] (of [[Christ]]) since the 14th century, generic use since the 17th century.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/ɪˈpɪf.ə.ni/|/ɛˈpɪf.ə.ni/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-epiphany.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{audio|en|en-au-epiphany.ogg|Audio (AU)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|epiphanies}}

# A [[manifestation]] or [[appearance]] of a [[divine]] or [[superhuman]] [[being]].
# An [[illuminating]] [[realization]] or [[discovery]], often resulting in a personal feeling of [[elation]], [[awe]], or [[wonder]].
# {{lb|en|Christianity}} {{alt case|en|Epiphany}}.

